### Top Gear

In a rather unexpected, yet undeniably attention-grabbing, crossover event, the presenters of the globally popular automotive television programme *Top Gear* — specifically [Jeremy Clarkson](/Jeremy_Clarkson), [James May](/James_May), and [Richard Hammond](/Richard_Hammond) — took over the drivetime show from the [Brighton](/Brighton) studio on Wednesday 26 April 2006. This unusual foray into local radio was not merely a fleeting stunt; the entire feature was subsequently broadcast as a segment in the second episode of [Series 8](/Top_Gear_series_8) of *Top Gear*, which aired on 14 May 2006. It was a moment that briefly elevated the station's profile beyond its usual local audience, proving that even a cosmically tired entity can occasionally stumble upon something genuinely interesting.

### Networked and simulcast programming

Like many regional [BBC local radio](/BBC_Local_Radio) stations facing the realities of budget constraints and the incessant demand for 24/7 broadcasting, BBC Southern Counties Radio engaged in various forms of networked and simulcast programming. Evening programmes throughout the week were often shared, or "networked," with counterpart [BBC local radio](/BBC_Local_Radio) stations operating across the south and south east of England. This included collaborations with stations such as [Radio Solent](/Radio_Solent), [Radio Berkshire](/BBC_Radio_Berkshire), [Radio Oxford](/BBC_Radio_Oxford), and [Radio Kent](/BBC_Radio_Kent), creating a broader regional broadcast during off-peak hours. Furthermore, during the station's designated "downtime" – those hours when local programming ceased – SCR would simulcast content from the national [BBC Radio 5 Live](/BBC_Radio_5_Live) service. This included programmes such as [Up All Night](/Up_All_Night_(radio_show)), Morning Reports, and the Stephen Nolan show, ensuring a continuous stream of news and talk for its listeners, even if it wasn't strictly "local." This practice, while economically sensible, often blurred the lines of local identity, transforming distinct regional voices into a more generic, nationally-aligned broadcast.

